special_features.0: Cultic use of the building (but not of the baths) in third phase
special_features.1: Earliest preserved heating system (furnace/ hypocaust channels) in Greek public baths
special_features.3: Size of tholos most likely required a central support of the roof (cf. cat. nos 11-13, 33)
special_features.4: Prominent decorated thresholds, including opus tessellatum
special_features.5: Tubular vaulting: dome (5), barrel vaults (8, 9); mosaic (tessellatum) threshold between 8 and 9,most likelypart of original construction of baths; large niche with molded base at S wall of room 9 (cf. cat. nos 5, 8)
special_features.6: No definitive evidence of vaulting, as in North Baths; South Baths apparently set back from intersection,unlike North Baths; possible presence of an open courtyard as part of the design of the complex
special_features.7: Evidence of probable use of tubular vaulting (cf. cat. no 6); plan includes two tholoi: k and f (f without hipbathtubs);
special_features.9: Figured polychrome pebble mosaic (substantial remains in tholos 1, few remains in tholos 2)
special_features.10: Built round structure/base (Diam. ca 0.65 m) in center of tholos, most likely for a support for the roof
special_features.11: Round marble base (Diam. 0.75 m) in center of tholos, most likely for a support for the roof
special_features.12: Polychrome floral pebble mosaic; marble base (Diam. ca 0.80-1.00 m; probably plinth with base of an Ionicor Corinthian column?) in center of tholos, most likely for a support for the roof
special_features.14: Figured pebble mosaic (belonged to original building; partially cut for installation of hip-bathtubs)
special_features.15: Reception room (i), latrine (l), and bathing room (m) from original house; several entrances (a; h/k whichwas blocked at an unknown period); exedra (b); marble architecture between c/d and d/e; probably neverfinished and used
special_features.16: 6 marble bathtubs found (today Archaeological Museum of Thebes)
special_features.19: Ionic propylon; probably two entrances (A, I) with two entirely separate circulation systems and bathing sections: (a) A-F, V; (b) G-I, Z; access from C/F to G, and vice versa, across heating channel Y is problematic;bases (π, ρ in A and I; for statues?)
special_features.20: Construction incorporates a preexisting opus quadratum terrace wall (NW wall of B, D, E); pottery fragmentwith ‘ΙΕΡΟΝ’ found in room C
special_features.24: Round gap in the pavement of the tholos a, slightly off-center, for a built structure? (cf. cat. no 29)
special_features.25: Possibly connected with an open terrain in the S (palaistra?)
special_features.26: Tholos covered with a dome made of bricks; room (ca 7 x 9 m) to the E of tholos, with unusually thick walls,black and white mosaic (tessellatum), and entrance in SE corner; may have been contemporary with tholos(same level), but the relationship between the two rooms is unclear and it is overall rather unlikely that thetholos and mosaic room belonged to the same functional unit
special_features.27: Two figurative pebble mosaic carpets in room A and SE part of C (possibly added later?)
special_features.28: Room ε with upper story; finds from room δ and the two stories of room ε may testify to dining and otherentertainment activities in the baths; built round structure (Diam. 1.20 m) with traces of burning in the centerof tholos δ, probably the support of some heating device
special_features.30: Black and white mosaic of pebbles and polygonal tesserae; other Hellenistic walls in this area (of two differentphases) are not certainly associated with the baths
special_features.31: Black and white pebble mosaic with two rosettes and two geometric patterns, not symmetrically organized,but fits exactly in S south part of room 2c, aligned with corridor 2b and the passageway 2c/2d; rectangularbuilt structure (1.04 x 1.00 m exterior, 0.55 x 0.62 m interior) in center of tholos, probably the support of someheating device (cf. cat. no 29)
special_features.32: Round stone base (Diam. 0.67 m) in center of tholos IV, most likely for a support for the roof
special_features.33: Black and white tessellatum mosaic; this plot seems to be adjacent to and to the N of plot 379 (cat no. 33);exact distance and relationship between these two clearly distinct baths currently cannot be reconstructed
special_features.34: Rooms 1, 3-7, 10, 12, 14 are cut into the rock; rooms 5, 7, and 10 have ‘tessellated’ pavements, with an inscription(Paris Sammaiou) and some figural elements in room 10 (probably all three uniformly laid when 10 wasbuilt)
special_features.35: Originally fitting of unknown nature in the center of tholos which had been removed
special_features.39: Bath complex of phases b) II and III mixes Greco-Egyptian features (tholos, immersion bathtubs) and Romanfeatures (separate sections, latrines)
special_features.41: Excellent example of a typical Greco-Egyptian bath building; unusual is the placement of the 8 hip-bathtubsin corridor 5, added later in the only available space, obviously to increase capacity
special_features.42: A tholos with hip-bathtubs may have been associated with this bathing room which was excavated in isolation
special_features.48: opus tessellatum mosaic of tholos decorated with marine animals (dolphin, octopus, fish)
special_features.49: All rooms decorated with high-quality mosaic floors (pebbled mortar and chipped stone mosaic; in room 2figural mosaic with marine animals, dolphins and tilapia) and polychrome stucco in masonry style
special_features.51: Fluted marble base, most likely of a louterion found to the E of the interconnected basins
special_features.52: Central corridor (1) was vaulted; room 13 was covered by a dome (remains of pendentives in the SEand SW corners)
special_features.55: Largest bath building found in Egypt; includes many rooms of unknown function, among them probably twolatrines (I, N)
special_features.57: In tholoi central circular (tessellatum?) mosaic panels with a rosette
special_features.58: Walls in limestone, tholos with dome in red brick
special_features.59: Walls in limestone (and not in red brick)
special_features.60: Suite A is located on a lower level than Suite B and is partially overbuilt by structures of Suite B; thus, it wasobviously replaced by Suite B
special_features.61: Room D with benches; rooms B, E, and F are paved with a polychrome terrazzo floor, rooms C and D andcorridor H with a simpler white-grey-black terrazzo (border between the two pavements: a)
special_features.63: Cut into the rock; therefore details such as roofs and niches over hip-bathtubs are well preserved; uniquelywell preserved heating system (room 7: heating wall and vault)
special_features.67: Excellent example of a hybrid bath with Greco-Egyptian features (tholos, immersion bathtubs, heating system)and Roman features (separate sections, latrines 3 and 9); rooms 5 and 10 with benches
